# ‚úÖ **How to Get Monitoring & Observability for Microsoft Copilot**

Microsoft Copilot (including **M365 Copilot**, **Copilot Studio agents**, and **custom AI agents**) does not expose *one single unified observability console* yet. However, **Microsoft provides multiple official paths** to achieve enterprise‚Äëgrade monitoring and observability.

Below are the **four primary ways** you can get monitoring and observability for Copilot today.

***

# üîç **1. Use Azure Copilot Observability Agent (Preview)**

If your Copilot integrates with **Azure Monitor** (common in enterprise scenarios), Microsoft offers an **AI-powered observability agent** that automatically:

*   Analyzes telemetry from Azure resources
*   Detects anomalies in logs & metrics
*   Correlates signals across systems
*   Generates root‚Äëcause findings with explanations
*   Integrates with alerts and the Azure Monitor workflow

üìå Source: Microsoft Learn ‚Äì Azure Copilot Observability Agent [\[learn.microsoft.com\]](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/azure-monitor/aiops/observability-agent-overview)

**Use Cases:**

*   Monitoring Copilot workflows tied to Azure functions, APIs, data stores
*   Automatic issue investigations
*   Post‚Äëincident diagnostics

***

# üîç **2. Connect Copilot Studio Agents to Azure Application Insights**

If you are building Copilot agents in **Copilot Studio**, Microsoft recommends using **Application Insights** for:

*   Real‚Äëtime telemetry
*   Logging & structured events
*   Conversation transcripts
*   Performance metrics (response times, errors, failures)
*   KQL-based analytics
*   Alerts & dashboards

üìå Source: Application Insights + Copilot Studio Integration Guide [\[reshmeeauckloo.com\]](https://reshmeeauckloo.com/posts/copilot-connecting-application-insights/)

**What You Can Monitor:**

*   User interactions
*   Message sequences
*   Success vs failure rates
*   Response delay outliers
*   Agent decision paths
*   Conversation drop‚Äëoffs

**Setup Steps (summary):**

1.  Create an Application Insights resource
2.  Link the connection string to your Copilot Studio agent
3.  View telemetry in Application Insights & Copilot Studio dashboard

***

# üîç **3. Use Microsoft‚Äôs Observability Guidance for Pro‚ÄëCode Copilot Apps**

If you are building **pro-code Copilot extensions**, plug-ins, or AI-powered workflows, Microsoft provides observability best practices:

*   Track LLM lifecycle signals
*   Instrument retrieval augmented generation (RAG)
*   Monitor exception handling
*   Evaluate prompt performance
*   Logging for safety & failure cases

üìå Source: Microsoft Cloud Observability for AI Solutions Guide [\[github.com\]](https://github.com/MicrosoftDocs/microsoft-cloud/blob/main/docs/dev/copilot/isv/Observability-for-AI.md)

This applies to:

*   Azure AI Foundry
*   Custom copilots
*   Complex multi-agent workflows
*   ISV solutions

***

# üîç **4. Use the Copilot Studio Monitor (Governance Tool)**

Because Copilot Studio lacks visibility for admins, the community-created **Copilot Studio Monitor** (built on the Power Platform CoE Kit) helps admins:

*   Inventory all Copilot agents
*   View agent configuration & connectors
*   Track knowledge sources
*   Identify risky or ungoverned agents
*   Feed data into Power BI dashboards

üìå Source: Copilot Studio Monitor ‚Äì PowerTricks [\[powertricks.io\]](https://powertricks.io/copilot-studio-monitor/)

This is especially useful for:

*   Tenant-wide visibility
*   Compliance and governance
*   Understanding agent behavior & dependencies

***

